body:
[
  {
    "type": "lead",
    "text": "If you are planning a house in Lahore in 2025, the smartest way to approach your budget is to separate the project into grey structure, finishing, and turnkey delivery. That gives you a much clearer picture of where the money is spent and helps you compare contractor quotations without confusion."
  },
  {
    "type": "stats",
    "statItems": [
      {
        "label": "Grey structure",
        "value": "Core build cost",
        "note": "Foundation, RCC frame, masonry, plaster, roofing, and rough MEP base work."
      },
      {
        "label": "Finishing",
        "value": "Visible quality layer",
        "note": "Flooring, paint, ceilings, kitchens, wardrobes, doors, sanitary, and fittings."
      },
      {
        "label": "Turnkey",
        "value": "Move-in ready",
        "note": "Single-point execution from structure through finishing and final handover."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "heading",
    "text": "Why cost per marla matters"
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "In Lahore, most homeowners begin budgeting with a per-marla estimate because it gives a fast planning benchmark before drawings and specifications are fully finalised. It is not the final contract number, but it is the most useful early-stage guide for deciding plot feasibility, finish expectations, and financing strategy."
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "A realistic estimate should always consider more than just covered area. Material quality, labour availability, structural complexity, and the standard of finishing all shift the final figure meaningfully."
  },
  {
    "type": "heading",
    "text": "The three cost layers every owner should understand"
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "Grey structure covers the skeleton of the house, including excavation, foundation, RCC frame, brickwork, plaster, roof slab, waterproofing, and the rough MEP base work. This is the part of the project where structural discipline matters most, and where poor-quality decisions become expensive later."
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "Finishing includes the visible character of the home. Flooring, paint, ceilings, kitchens, wardrobes, doors, sanitary fittings, electrical accessories, and facade detailing all sit in this layer. Two houses with the same structure can differ dramatically in cost once finishing selections begin."
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "Turnkey means the house is delivered in move-in-ready condition. This usually includes structure, finishing, coordination, procurement, quality control, and final handover. For many clients, turnkey is the cleaner route because it reduces fragmented decision-making and keeps responsibility clearer."
  },
  {
    "type": "callout",
    "title": "Practical planning tip",
    "text": "Set your budget in phases. Lock the grey-structure number first, add a realistic finishing allowance, and keep a contingency margin of 10 to 15 percent for market movement and design upgrades."
  },
  {
    "type": "heading",
    "text": "What usually increases construction cost in Lahore"
  },
  {
    "type": "bullets",
    "title": "The most common cost drivers",
    "bulletItems": [
      "Higher steel, cement, and brick specifications",
      "Premium tile, marble, porcelain, or imported finishes",
      "Complex front elevation and facade treatments",
      "Custom kitchens, wardrobes, and joinery",
      "Larger electrical scope with feature lighting and smart controls",
      "Landscaping, boundary wall upgrades, and external development"
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "heading",
    "text": "Area-by-area budget positioning"
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "Different Lahore localities come with different client expectations, labour conditions, and finish standards. That is why the same size house may sit in a different budget band depending on where it is being built."
  },
  {
    "type": "table",
    "tableRows": [
      {
        "area": "DHA Lahore",
        "positioning": "Upper mid to premium",
        "expectation": "Strong detailing, cleaner execution, and premium fixtures"
      },
      {
        "area": "Gulberg",
        "positioning": "Premium",
        "expectation": "Architect-led finishes, refined interiors, and high presentation value"
      },
      {
        "area": "Bahria Town",
        "positioning": "Mid to upper mid",
        "expectation": "Balanced pricing with flexibility across finish ranges"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "heading",
    "text": "How to compare quotations properly"
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "One of the most common mistakes homeowners make is comparing two contractor quotes that are based on different assumptions. A lower quote often excludes details that appear later as variations, while a higher quote may already include better structure, more fittings, or cleaner finishing."
  },
  {
    "type": "bullets",
    "title": "Compare every quotation against the same scope",
    "bulletItems": [
      "Structural specification and slab details",
      "Brand level for electrical and plumbing materials",
      "Tile, sanitary, and woodwork allowances",
      "External works and boundary wall coverage",
      "Supervision, site management, and finishing responsibility"
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "heading",
    "text": "A realistic way to use this article"
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "Treat this post as a planning benchmark, not a final promise. Once your drawings, finish selections, and engineering decisions are properly defined, your cost estimate becomes much more accurate. That is the stage where professional budgeting creates real value."
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "text": "For homeowners building in DHA, Gulberg, Bahria Town, or surrounding Lahore areas, the best results usually come from clear specifications, disciplined quality control, and early alignment between design expectations and available budget."
  }
]
